ent":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Notes:<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>","source":"**Notes:**"},{"content":"Each operation can have only one successor operation, and the whole route must end in a single operation.","pos":[4811,4916]},{"content":"There is no guarantee that multiple operations that have the same successor operation (for example, operations 30 and 40 in the preceding illustration) will actually be run in parallel.","pos":[4921,5106]},{"content":"The availability and capacity of resources might put constraints on the way that operations are scheduled.","pos":[5107,5213]},{"content":"You can't use 0 (zero) as the operation number.","pos":[5218,5265]},{"content":"That number is reserved and is used to specify that the last operation in the route has no successor operation.","pos":[5266,5377]},{"pos":[5383,5402],"content":"Parallel operations","linkify":"Parallel operations","nodes":[{"content":"Parallel operations","pos":[0,19]}]},{"content":"Sometimes, a combination of multiple operations resources that have different characteristics is required in order to perform an operation.","pos":[5404,5543]},{"content":"For example, an assembly operation might require a machine, a tool, and one worker for every two machines to oversee the operation.","pos":[5544,5675]},{"content":"This example can be modeled by using parallel operations, where one operation is designated as the primary operation and the others are secondary.","pos":[5676,5822]},{"pos":[5826,5992],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><ph id=\"ph1\">![</ph>Route that has primary and secondary operations<ept id=\"p1\">](./media/routes-and-operations-3-parallel-operations.png)](./media/routes-and-operations-3-parallel-operations.png)</ept>","source":"[![Route that has primary and secondary operations](./media/routes-and-operations-3-parallel-operations.png)](./media/routes-and-operations-3-parallel-operations.png)"},{"content":"Typically, the primary operation represents the bottleneck resource and dictates the run time for the secondary operations.","pos":[5996,6119]},{"content":"However, during scheduling that involves finite capacity, the resources that are scheduled for both the primary operation and the secondary operations must be available and have free capacity at the same time.","pos":[6120,6329]},{"content":"Both the primary operation and the secondary operations must have the same operation number (30 in the preceding illustration).","pos":[6333,6460]},{"content":"In the preceding example, the resource requirement for the primary operation (30) is the machine, whereas the resource requirements for the secondary operations (30' and 30'') are the tool and the worker.","pos":[6464,6668]},{"content":"A fifty-percent load helps guarantee that the scheduled worker can oversee two machines at the same time.","pos":[6669,6774]},{"pos":[6780,6798],"content":"Approval of routes","linkify":"Approval of routes","nodes":[{"content":"Approval of routes","pos":[0,18]}]},{"content":"A route must be approved before it can be used in the planning or manufacturing process.","pos":[6800,6888]},{"content":"Approval indicates that the route design has been completed.","pos":[6889,6949]},{"content":"The same released product or released product variant can have multiple approved routes.","pos":[6950,7038]},{"content":"Typically, approval of a route occurs when the first relevant route version is approved.","pos":[7039,7127]},{"content":"However, in some business scenarios, the approval of the route and the route version are separate activities that might involve different process owners.","pos":[7128,7281]},{"content":"Each route can be approved or unapproved separately.","pos":[7285,7337]},{"content":"However, note that, when a route is unapproved, all related route versions are also unapproved.","pos":[7338,7433]},{"content":"In the Production control parameters, you can specify whether routes can be unapproved, and whether approved routes can be changed.","pos":[7434,7565]},{"content":"If you must keep a log that records who approves each route, you can require electronic signatures for route approval.","pos":[7569,7687]},{"content":"Users will then have to confirm their identity by using an <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>electronic signature<ept id=\"p1\">](/dynamics365/unified-operations/fin-and-ops/organization-administration/electronic-signature-overview)</ept>.","pos":[7688,7873],"source":" Users will then have to confirm their identity by using an [electronic signature](/dynamics365/unified-operations/fin-and-ops/organization-administration/electronic-signature-overview)."},{"pos":[7878,7888],"content":"Operations","linkify":"Operations","nodes":[{"content":"Operations","pos":[0,10]}]},{"content":"An operation is a step in the production process.","pos":[7889,7938]},{"content":"In Finance and Operations, each operation has an ID and a simple description.","pos":[7939,8016]},{"content":"The following tables shows typical examples of operations from a machine shop.","pos":[8017,8095]},{"content":"Operation","pos":[8099,8108]},{"content":"Description","pos":[8112,8123]},{"content":"PipeCut","pos":[8171,8178]},{"content":"Pipe cutting","pos":[8184,8196]},{"content":"TIGweld","pos":[8207,8214]},{"content":"TIG welding","pos":[8220,8231]},{"content":"JigAssy","pos":[8243,8250]},{"content":"Jig assembly","pos":[8256,8268]},{"content":"Inspection","pos":[8279,8289]},{"content":"Quality inspection","pos":[8292,8310]},{"content":"The operational properties of the operation, such as the setup time and run time, resource requirements, costing information, and consumption calculation, are specified on the operation relation.","pos":[8314,8509]},{"content":"(For more information about operation relations, see the next section.)","pos":[8510,8581]},{"pos":[8586,8605],"content":"Operation relations","linkify":"Operation relations","nodes":[{"content":"Operation relations","pos":[0,19]}]},{"content":"The following operational properties of an operation are maintained on the operation relation:","pos":[8606,8700]},{"content":"Cost categories","pos":[8706,8721]},{"content":"Consumption parameters","pos":[8726,8748]},{"content":"Processing times","pos":[8753,8769]},{"content":"Processing quantities","pos":[8774,8795]},{"content":"Resource requirements","pos":[8800,8821]},{"content":"Notes and instructions","pos":[8826,8848]},{"content":"You can define multiple operation relations for the same operation.","pos":[8850,8917]},{"content":"However, each operation relation is specific to one operation, and stores properties that are specific to a route, a released product, or a set of released products that are related to an item group.","pos":[8918,9117]},{"content":"Therefore, the same operation can be used in multiple routes that have different operational properties.","pos":[9118,9222]},{"content":"In addition, you can more easily maintain your master data if you use standard operations that have the same operational properties, regardless of the route that is used and product that is produced.","pos":[9223,9422]},{"content":"The scope of the operation relation is defined through the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Item code<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>, <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Item relation<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept>, <bpt id=\"p3\">**</bpt>Route code<ept id=\"p3\">**</ept> and <bpt id=\"p4\">**</bpt>Route relation<ept id=\"p4\">**</ept> properties, as shown in the following table.","pos":[9423,9598],"source":" The scope of the operation relation is defined through the **Item code**, **Item relation**, **Route code** and **Route relation** properties, as shown in the following table."},{"content":"Item code","pos":[9602,9611]},{"content":"Item relation","pos":[9614,9627]},{"content":"Route code","pos":[9638,9648]},{"content":"Route relation","pos":[9651,9665]},{"content":"Scope of the operation relation","pos":[9670,9701]},{"content":"Table","pos":[10348,10353]},{"content":"<ph id=\"ph1\">&amp;lt;</ph>Item ID<ph id=\"ph2\">&amp;gt;</ph>","pos":[10360,1